[{"id":"VR217160","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<p class=\"title_line passage-title\">&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A. Using the location shown in Image 2, describe the pilgrimage location in terms of sequent occupance.</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">B. Explain how the global population distribution of a universalizing religion relates to the religion’s place of origin.</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">C. Using the location shown in Image 1, explain how a pilgrimage site can create cultural convergence among peoples of different ethnicities.</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">D. Explain ONE way that expansion diffusion can account for the patterns of international travel to pilgrimage locations.</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">E. Explain ONE way that conflicts over the control of pilgrimage sites can lead to the devolution of a state.</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR217160_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<p class=\"title_line passage-title\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">IMAGE 1: MASJID AL-HARAM OR GREAT MOSQUE, MECCA</span></p>\n</div>\n<img alt=\"Image 1 presents a photograph of the Great Mosque in Mecca.  The Kaaba, a large, cube shaped building, is shown at the center of the photograph. Large crowds of people are shown tightly packed, surrounding the Kaaba.The figure presents a line graph titled Grain Yields in Pounds per Acre, for Selected Regions. The horizontal axis is labeled Years, and the years 1960 through 2015, in increments of 5 years, are indicated. The vertical axis is labeled Pounds per Acre, and the numbers 0 through 6,000, in increments of 1,000, are indicated. Five lines are shown in the line graph. A key indicates that the lines represent the following five categories: Europe, East Asia and Pacific, World, Latin America and Caribbean, and Sub-Saharan Africa. The data in the line graph are as follows. Note that all values are approximate. The line representing Europe begins at 1,600 pounds per acre in 1960. It moves generally upward and to the right, reaching 2,700 in 1975, 4,300 in 1990, 4,700 in 2005, and 5,100 in 2015. The line representing East Asia and Pacific begins at 1,200 pounds per acre in 1960. It moves generally upward and to the right, reaching 2,100 in 1975, 3,300 in 1990, 3,900 in 2005, and 4,600 in 2015. The line representing the World begins at 1,200 pounds per acre in 1960. It moves generally upward and to the right, reaching 1,900 in 1975, 2,500 in 1990, 3,000 in 2005, and 3,800 in 2015. The line representing Latin America and Caribbean begins at 1,100 in 1960. It moves generally upward and to the right, reaching 1,500 in 1975, 2,200 in 1990, 3,000 in 2005, and 4,400 in 2015. The line representing Sub-Saharan Africa begins at 800 in 1960. It moves very gradually upward, reaching 875 in 1975, 850 in 1990, 1,000 in 2005, and 1,300 in 2015.\" height=\"450\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR217160.g01.png\" width=\"600\" /><span class=\"mandatory_credit_line\">© ayazad/Shutterstock.com</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<p class=\"title_line passage-title\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">IMAGE 2: KOTEL, WAILING WALL, OR WESTERN WALL, JERUSALEM</span></p>\n</div>\n<img alt=\"Image 2 presents the Western Wall in Jerusalem, which is also known as the Wailing Wall or Kotel. A large crowd of people are shown throughout the photograph, in front of the wall.\" height=\"400\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR217160.g02.png\" width=\"600\" /><span class=\"mandatory_credit_line\">© dbimages / Alamy # B7B7FH</span></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Pilgrimage is commonly practiced by religious followers around the world. Each year, millions of pilgrims travel to pilgrimage locations in other countries.</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">&nbsp;</p>\n"}]}]